==Old English==
===Etymology===
Common Germanic *''[[auson]]'', from Indo-European ''*h₂ous-''.

''Germanic cognates:'' Old Frisian ''āre'', Old Saxon ''[[ōra]]'' (Dutch ''[[oor]]''), Old High German ''[[ōra]]'' (German ''[[Ohr]]''), Old Norse ''[[eyra]]'' (Swedish ''[[öra]]''), Gothic [[𐌰𐌿𐍃𐍉]].

''Indo-European cognates:'' Greek [[οὖς]], Latin ''[[auris]]'', Common Slavic ''[[uho]]'' (Russian [[ухо]]), Old Irish [[au]].

